---
id: org.dxos.plugin.trip
name: TripPlugin
version: 0.1.0
---

A Composer plugin for managing travel itineraries. A `Trip` is an ordered
list of typed `Segment`s (Flight, Train, Boat, Road, Lodging, Activity),
each of which may be associated with a `Booking` (the actual ticket / reservation). 
Trips can be browsed individually or in aggregate via existing Table and Map views, 
presented as Articles, or embedded as surfaces inside Markdown documents.

v1 ships the data model plus two cross-plugin integrations:

- A `TravelMessageExtractor` that plugs into plugin-inbox's
  generic `MessageExtractor` contract to parse confirmation emails
  into `Booking`s + `Segment`s.
- A `TripCalendarSource` that plugs into plugin-inbox's
  `CalendarEventSource` contract to project `Segment`s as calendar
  events, so trips render directly on the calendar without a dual
  write to materialised events.

Future work (deferred from v1):

- `SegmentRequest` — a "desired multi-leg travel" shape that feeds a
  search provider and produces candidate `Segment`s + `Booking`s.
- A `BookingFor` ECHO relation linking `Booking` → `Trip` (queries
  currently reach bookings via `Trip.segments[].booking`).

## Extensions

The following extension dialects are used in this document.
Each extension is defined in the Appendix or resolved via its URI.

| Term     | URI                          |
| -------- | ---------------------------- |
| `type`   | `org.dxos.mdl.type@1.0`      |
| `feat`   | `org.dxos.mdl.feat@1.0`      |
| `op`     | `org.dxos.mdl.op@1.0`        |
| `test`   | `org.dxos.mdl.test@1.0`      |

## Cross-package additions

Some types and contracts referenced here are added outside `plugin-trip` because they are generally useful:

| Symbol                | Package                | Notes                                                                                              |
| --------------------- | ---------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `Provider`            | `@dxos/types`          | New plain `Schema.Struct`. Parallel to `Actor`. Used wherever a third-party service is referenced. |
| `Account`             | `@dxos/types`          | New ECHO object (`org.dxos.type.account`). Loyalty / membership accounts at providers.             |
| `MessageExtractor`    | `plugin-inbox`         | New generic contract. plugin-trip registers `TravelMessageExtractor`.                              |
| `ExtractedFrom`       | `plugin-inbox`         | New ECHO relation. Source = extracted object, target = source `Message`.                           |
| `CalendarEventSource` | `plugin-inbox`         | New generic contract. plugin-trip registers `TripCalendarSource`.                                  |
| `CalendarEventLike`   | `plugin-inbox`         | Uniform projection shape returned by `CalendarEventSource` impls.                                  |

## Types

### Existing types used by this plugin

| Type           | Source                  | Typename                       | Role                                                  |
| -------------- | ----------------------- | ------------------------------ | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| `Organization` | `@dxos/types`           | `org.dxos.type.organization`   | Optional rich link target for `Provider.ref`.         |
| `Person`       | `@dxos/types`           | `org.dxos.type.person`         | Optional link for passengers on a `Booking`.          |
| `File`         | `@dxos/types`           | `org.dxos.type.file`           | Attachment target for booking PDFs / e-tickets.       |
| `GeoPoint`     | `@dxos/echo` (`Format`) | (system)                       | Optional geometry on `Place`.                         |
| `DateTime`     | `@dxos/echo` (`Format`) | (system)                       | Used for `departAt`, `arriveAt`, `checkIn`, etc.      |
| `Hostname`     | `@dxos/echo` (`Format`) | (system)                       | Used for `Provider.domain`.                           |

### New shared types (added to `@dxos/types`)

```mdl
type Provider
  desc: >
    Reference to an external service or company — airline, hotel chain,
    rail operator, ticketing platform, etc. Parallel to Actor: a human
    label + machine identifier + optional Ref to a rich object. Plain
    Schema.Struct (not a Type.object); embedded inline by callers.
  fields:
    name?: string                   # e.g. "United Airlines"
    domain?: Hostname               # e.g. "united.com"
    ref?: Ref<Organization>         # rich link once an Organization exists
```

```mdl
type Account
  typename: org.dxos.type.account
  desc: >
    A user's account / membership with an external service. Used for
    loyalty programs (frequent flyer, hotel rewards), travel profiles,
    ticketing accounts, and any non-credential identity at a third-party
    provider. Distinct from AccessToken, which holds the credential to
    call APIs on behalf of an account.
  fields:
    provider: Provider              # who the account is with
    kind?: 'airline' | 'rail' | 'hotel' | 'car' | 'cruise' | 'travel' | 'other'
    accountNumber?: string          # loyalty / membership number
    displayName?: string            # name on account, e.g. "R. Burdon"
    tier?: string                   # "Gold", "1K", "Diamond"
    status?: 'active' | 'expired'
    notes?: string
    accessTokens?: Ref<AccessToken>[]  # optional credential link
  annotations:
    icon: ph--identification-card--regular
    label: [displayName, provider.name]
```

### New plugin-trip types

```mdl
type Place
  desc: >
    Generic location shape used as origin / destination on every Segment.
    Embedded inline. Uniform across modes so Table and Map views can
    consume Segments without per-variant branching.
  fields:
    name?: string                   # "London Heathrow", "Hotel Costes", ...
    code?: string                   # IATA / IBNR / port / property code
    city?: string
    country?: string                # ISO 3166 alpha-2 preferred
    geo?: GeoPoint
```

```mdl
type SegmentCore
  desc: >
    Shared fields present on every Segment variant. Not a standalone
    type — embedded by each variant in the Segment union below.
  fields:
    id: string                      # stable per-trip id (survives status changes)
    # tentative: user-authored placeholder ("we'll fly Tuesday-ish").
    # proposed:  extractor / agent suggestion awaiting user accept.
    # confirmed: backed by a real Booking.
    # cancelled: kept for history; rendered de-emphasised.
    status: 'tentative' | 'proposed' | 'confirmed' | 'cancelled'
    origin?: Place
    destination?: Place
    departAt?: DateTime
    arriveAt?: DateTime
    booking?: Ref<Booking>          # absent for tentative / proposed
    notes?: string
```

```mdl
type FlightSegment
  desc: Air travel leg.
  fields:
    ...SegmentCore
    kind: 'flight'
    airline?: Provider
    flightNumber?: string
    cabin?: 'economy' | 'premium' | 'business' | 'first'
    terminalFrom?: string
    terminalTo?: string
    gateFrom?: string
    gateTo?: string
    seat?: string
```

```mdl
type TrainSegment
  desc: Rail travel leg.
  fields:
    ...SegmentCore
    kind: 'train'
    operator?: Provider
    trainNumber?: string
    class?: string
    coach?: string
    seat?: string
```

```mdl
type BoatSegment
  desc: Water travel leg. Covers ferry and cruise (split deferred to v2).
  fields:
    ...SegmentCore
    kind: 'boat'
    operator?: Provider
    vessel?: string
    cabin?: string
```

```mdl
type RoadSegment
  desc: >
    Road travel leg. subKind discriminates the mode while keeping the
    union small. "transfer" covers private cars / shuttles; "walk" lets
    itineraries express walking legs without a separate variant.
  fields:
    ...SegmentCore
    kind: 'road'
    subKind: 'bus' | 'car' | 'transfer' | 'taxi' | 'walk'
    operator?: Provider             # bus line, rental company, transfer co
    vehicleClass?: string
```

```mdl
type LodgingSegment
  desc: >
    Accommodation — a "stationary" segment. checkIn / checkOut mirror
    departAt / arriveAt so uniform time-range queries work, but are
    surfaced explicitly for clarity in UIs. origin and destination both
    point at the property location.
  fields:
    ...SegmentCore
    kind: 'lodging'
    operator?: Provider             # hotel chain / platform
    propertyName?: string           # specific property name
    roomType?: string
    checkIn?: DateTime
    checkOut?: DateTime
```

```mdl
type ActivitySegment
  desc: Tour, dinner reservation, ticketed event, etc. Point in time at a venue.
  fields:
    ...SegmentCore
    kind: 'activity'
    title: string
    operator?: Provider             # tour company / venue operator
    venue?: Place
```

```mdl
type Segment
  desc: Tagged union of all segment variants. Discriminated by `kind`.
  union:
    - FlightSegment
    - TrainSegment
    - BoatSegment
    - RoadSegment
    - LodgingSegment
    - ActivitySegment
```

```mdl
type Trip
  typename: org.dxos.type.trip
  desc: >
    Itinerary container. Segments are stored inline in itinerary order.
    No tags field — uses Obj.getMeta(trip).tags like all ECHO objects.
    No travellers / currency on the Trip — those live on each Booking,
    since per-segment travellers (e.g., colleagues joining for one leg)
    are common.
  fields:
    name?: string
    summary?: string                # short markdown description
    startDate?: DateTime            # explicit so a Trip can exist before any segments
    endDate?: DateTime
    segments: Segment[]             # inline, ordered = itinerary order
  annotations:
    icon: ph--airplane-takeoff--regular
    label: [name]
```

```mdl
type Booking
  typename: org.dxos.type.trip.booking
  desc: >
    A purchased ticket / reservation. One Booking may back multiple
    Segments (e.g., round-trip under a single PNR, or a multi-leg
    journey on one record locator).
  fields:
    provider?: Provider             # carrier / lodging chain / ticketing platform
    confirmationCode?: string       # PNR / record locator
    bookedUnder?: Ref<Account>      # account the booking was made under
    passengers?: { name: string; account?: Ref<Account>; person?: Ref<Person> }[]
    currency?: string               # ISO 4217
    totalPrice?: number
    purchasedAt?: DateTime
    source?: 'manual' | 'email' | 'agent' | 'import'
    rawPayload?: string             # original JSON / parsed email body
    attachments?: Ref<File>[]       # PDFs, e-tickets, boarding passes
  annotations:
    icon: ph--ticket--regular
    label: [confirmationCode, provider.name]
```

## Contracts consumed (new in plugin-inbox)

These are generic — defined in plugin-inbox so any plugin can implement
them. plugin-trip provides one impl of each.

```mdl
type MessageExtractor
  desc: >
    Pluggable handler invoked by plugin-inbox on Messages. Each
    extractor advertises a cheap match predicate and an extract step
    that produces ECHO objects (e.g., Booking + Segments) and links
    them back to the source Message via an ExtractedFrom relation.
  fields:
    id: string                      # stable identifier, e.g. "trip-travel"
    description: string             # shown in inbox UI / extractor picker
    kinds: string[]                 # coarse hints, e.g. ["flight", "hotel"]
    match: (msg: Message) => MatchResult
    extract: (ctx, msg: Message) => Promise<ExtractResult>
```

```mdl
type MatchResult
  fields:
    matched: boolean
    confidence?: number             # 0–1; used to rank multiple matches
    reason?: string

type ExtractResult
  fields:
    created: Ref<Obj>[]             # objects created in the space
    relations: Ref<Relation>[]      # e.g. ExtractedFrom relations
    summary?: string                # for activity log / toast
```

```mdl
type ExtractedFrom
  desc: ECHO relation. source = extracted object; target = source Message.
  fields:
    extractorId: string
    extractedAt: DateTime
  relation:
    source: Obj                     # the extracted object (Booking, Segment, ...)
    target: Message                 # org.dxos.type.message
```

```mdl
type CalendarEventSource
  desc: >
    Pluggable contract used by calendar views. plugin-inbox queries every
    registered source for a time range and merges the results. Avoids
    dual-writing materialised CalendarEvents.
  fields:
    id: string                      # e.g. "trip-segments"
    description: string
    query: (range: { from: DateTime; to: DateTime }) => CalendarEventLike[]
```

```mdl
type CalendarEventLike
  desc: Uniform shape returned by CalendarEventSource implementations.
  fields:
    id: string                      # source-stable, e.g. "trip:<trip>:seg:<seg>"
    title: string                   # "UA 904  SFO → LHR"
    start: DateTime
    end?: DateTime
    location?: Place
    sourceObject?: Ref<Obj>         # the underlying Segment / Booking / etc.
    kind?: string                   # 'travel-flight' | 'travel-hotel' | ...
    color?: string                  # optional theming hint
```

### Inbox dispatch modes

plugin-inbox supports three dispatch modes for `MessageExtractor`s; the
mode is configured per `Mailbox`:

- **manual** — user picks an extractor on an opened message; always available.
- **agent-assisted** — extractors are exposed as tools the inbox / sidekick blueprint can call.
- **auto-on-arrival** — extractors run on new messages; the top match above a configurable confidence threshold extracts automatically. Off by default; opt-in per Mailbox.

## Implementations contributed by this plugin

```mdl
feat TravelMessageExtractor
  desc: >
    plugin-trip's MessageExtractor impl. Matches confirmation emails for
    flights, trains, hotels, ferries, cruises, car rentals, and ticketed
    activities. Produces a Booking and one or more Segments, links them
    back to the source Message via ExtractedFrom, and either appends to
    a Trip selected by the user / agent or wraps them in a new Trip.
  inputs:
    message: Message
    target?: Ref<Trip>              # optional Trip to append into
  outputs:
    booking: Booking
    segments: Segment[]
    extracted: ExtractedFrom[]
    trip?: Trip                     # newly created when no target
  notes:
    - Populates Provider.domain from sender email host; Provider.name from a known-domain lookup.
    - Dedupes Account by (provider.domain, accountNumber); creates Account on first encounter.
    - Initial implementation may use a heuristic parser; an agent-backed parser is a follow-up.
```

```mdl
feat TripCalendarSource
  desc: >
    plugin-trip's CalendarEventSource impl. Projects Segments into
    CalendarEventLike values on demand; no materialised events are
    written. Tentative segments are included with a "tentative" hint
    (color / opacity left to the renderer).
  outputs (per Segment kind):
    - flight | train | boat | road: start = departAt, end = arriveAt
    - lodging: start = checkIn, end = checkOut
    - activity: start = departAt; end optional
  notes:
    - id format: `trip:<trip-id>:seg:<seg-id>` so projections are stable across query calls.
    - sourceObject is set to a Ref of the underlying Segment so consumers can navigate to it.
```

## Out of scope for v1

- View definitions for Table / Map. The existing Table and Map view
  configurations are sufficient — Segments and Trips become queryable
  data sources for those views without new type contributions here.
- Markdown embedding surfaces. Trips and Segments use the generic
  article / embedded-surface mechanisms; no plugin-specific surface
  types are added.
- Currency conversion and price roll-ups. These are derived and live in
  view-side logic.
- `SegmentRequest` — multi-leg "desired travel" search input. Added when
  a real search provider is wired.
- `BookingFor` relation linking `Booking` → `Trip`. Added when a query
  needs Bookings without walking Segments.
- Splitting `BoatSegment` into ferry vs. cruise, and `RoadSegment` into
  per-mode variants. Revisit when usage demands richer per-mode typing.

## Open follow-ups

- Confirm whether `Provider` should also replace `AccessToken.source`
  (currently `Hostname`); out of scope here but worth a follow-up to
  keep the model uniform.
- Decide whether `Mailbox` grows an explicit `extractors[]` config or
  whether enablement is purely runtime via plugin registration.
